source.body: Hello Sigma Team!

Hi, I have a column from bigquery and it is using BIGNUMERIC. It is not casting into numeric data columns. Could you check?

The BigQuery BIGNUMERIC data type is used for exact numeric values with high precision and scale, ideal for applications like financial and scientific calculations that require a large number of digits.

Incident Summary for R&D
Root Cause: The API server at api.us.azure.sigmacomputing.com intermittently fails to return the required Access-Control-Allow-Origin header.

Trigger: The failure specifically occurs when the graphql2 call type defaults to JSON rather than Script.

Proof: DevTools logs show the browser enforcing its CORS policy and blocking the frontend's request from app.sigmacomputing.com.

In this control, I've set an action to "On Change" to show the specific columns I want for each option of the control. Changing the option of the control properly shows the columns I want to see in the workbook.

The issue is when exporting. When I schedule an export, it doesn't show the correct columns for each option of the control. Maybe it's because the action is set to "On Change", and exporting while selecting an option in the control doesn't actually change it? Hi Sigma Support Team,

I’m working with dashboards where multiple charts use the same source table, and we’ve added a Sigma Form–based input table to capture comments/anomalies by date and chart name.

Currently, to make comments appear only on the relevant charts, we need to create a joined parent/child table element and then use that as the source for multiple charts. This works, but it adds extra maintenance overhead for existing dashboards.

I wanted to check:

Is there any supported way to join an input table once and then, using only chart-level filters, control which charts display the associated comment, without creating child table elements?

Are there any upcoming enhancements that would allow:

Chart-level joins, or

Using chart-level calculated fields (e.g., chart name) as part of join conditions?

If neither is currently supported, is there a recommended best practice from Sigma for handling chart-specific annotations/comments at scale?

Appreciate any guidance or confirmation on current limitations and future plans.

Thanks,
Rozeen Nazir
